class Solution {
    public int removeDuplicates(int[] nums) {
        // ✅ Edge case: if the array is empty, there are no unique elements
        if (nums.length == 0) {
            return 0;
        }

        // ✅ 'i' is the slow pointer:
        // It tracks the position of the last unique element found.
        int i = 0;

        // ✅ 'j' is the fast pointer:
        // It scans through the array starting from index 1.
        for (int j = 1; j < nums.length; j++) {
            // If the current element nums[j] is different from nums[i],
            // it means we found a new unique element.
            if (nums[j] != nums[i]) {
                // Move the slow pointer forward to make space for the new unique element.
                i++;
                // Copy the unique element to the position after the last unique element.
                nums[i] = nums[j];
            }
            // If nums[j] == nums[i], it's a duplicate → skip it.
        }

        // ✅ The number of unique elements is (i + 1),
        // because 'i' is zero-based index of the last unique element.
        return i + 1;
    }
}

\\  Time Complexity: 
    𝑂(𝑛) → single pass through the array.

\\  Space Complexity: 
    𝑂(1) → in-place, no extra storage.

\\ Two-pointer technique:
   Efficient way to handle sorted arrays with duplicates.
